definition.value: Any of a class of 10--60 kDa glycosaminoglycan sulfates, widely distributed in cartilage and other mammalian connective tissues.
Any ether in which the oxygen atom forms part of a ring.

A heterodetic cyclic peptide consisting of eight amino acid residues and containing a thioether bridge between a cysteine and a tryptophan residue. It is found in a number of poisonous mushrooms, including Amanita phalloides (the death cap), Galerina marginata, and and Conocybe filaris.
An EC 2.7.7.* (nucleotidyltransferase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of RNA polymerase (EC 2.7.7.6).
Any beta-D-glucoside derived from a sterol.
A group of heterocyclic compounds based on the pteroic acid skeleton conjugated with one or more L-glutamic acid units.
A carbohydrate-containing antibiotic that is the  semisynthetic derivative of lincomycin, a natural antibiotic.
A D-galactose phosphate that consists of  D-galactopyranose having a single phospho substituent located at the 1-position. It is an intermediate obtained during the the galactose metabolism.

3-Isopropylimino-3,5-dihydro-phenazine in which the hydrogen at position 5 is substituted substituted by a 4-chlorophenyl group, and that at position 2 is substituted by a (4-chlorophenyl)amino group. A dark red crystalline solid, clofazimine is an antimycobacterial and is one of the main drugs used for the treatment of  multi-bacillary leprosy. However, it can cause red/brown discolouration of the skin, so other treatments are often preferred in light-skinned patients.
An acid is a molecular entity capable of donating a hydron (Bronsted acid) or capable of forming a covalent bond with an electron pair (Lewis acid).

Esters of phorbol, originally found in croton oil (from Croton tiglium, of the family Euphorbiaceae). A number of phorbol esters possess activity as tumour promoters and activate the mechanisms associated with cell growth. Some of these are used in experiments as activators of protein kinase C.
Derivatives of diazene with the general structure R-N=N-R'.
A phosphosphingolipid that consists of sphingosine having a phospho group attached at position 1
A nucleoside triphosphate(4-) obtained by global deprotonation of the triphosphate OH groups of CTP; major species present at pH 7.3.
A nucleoside triphosphate(4-) obtained by global deprotonation of the triphosphate OH groups of GTP; major species present at pH 7.3.
A molecular entity consisting of two or more chemical elements.
Any heteroatomic molecular entity that is a chemical compound of halogen with other chemical elements.
A lactone having a five-membered lactone ring.
An alkene that is octadecane containing one double bond at unspecified position.
The L-enantiomer of galactopyranose.
A L-galactopyranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.
The pyranose form of galactose.
An amide of a carboxylic acid, having the structure RC(=O)NR2. The term is used as a suffix in systematic name formation to denote the -C(=O)NH2 group including its carbon atom.
The L-enantiomer of glucopyranose.
A L-glucopyranose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric position.
A L-glucopyranose with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.
A compound which inhibits or antagonizes the biosynthesis or actions of proteases (endopeptidases).
An aldohexose that is the C-2 epimer of glucose.
An EC 2.7.* (P-containing group transferase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of protein kinases.
An EC 2.7.11.* (protein-serine/threonine kinase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of protein kinase C (EC 2.7.11.13).
A serine derivative that is serine substituted at the oxygen atom by a phosphono group.
Any imide in which the acyl substituents are any two from carboacyl, sulfonyl and phosphoryl
An EC 3.1.1.* (carboxylic ester hydrolase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of cholinesterase (EC 3.1.1.8).
Any glycerolipid having a phosphate group ester-linked to a terminal carbon of the glycerol backbone.
An organosulfonic acid containing one or more amino groups.
